<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Opening Strategy with A</h2>

<p>As the first player, A-words offer distinct opening advantages. A is worth 1 point and appears 9 times in the 100-tile bag. With multiple copies available, you will see it frequently — focus on learning the highest-scoring combinations.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Opening Move Tip</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">On the first turn, any word crossing the centre star gets a double-word bonus. A 1-point A in a five-letter word starting on the centre square can easily score <span class="text-white font-medium">10+ points</span> on your very first play.</p>
</div>

<p>Beyond openings, A-words are valuable for extending plays. When an opponent places a word ending near a triple-word square, starting a new word with A perpendicular to their play can capture that premium. This defensive-offensive approach — scoring well while denying your opponent access to premium squares — separates intermediate players from advanced ones.</p>

<p>Build your A-vocabulary in layers. Start with the two and three-letter A-words for tight board situations, then master the five and six-letter words for solid mid-game plays, and finally study the seven-letter bingo candidates that start with A. This progressive approach ensures you always have an A-word available regardless of board state.</p>

